<DocsLayout title="Evidence and readiness"><p class="eyebrow">Explanation</p><h1>Evidence and readiness</h1><p class="lede">The package version is intentionally boring. Readiness comes from what was executed against the packed artifact.</p>
<h2>Package proof</h2><p>Each library receipt covers deterministic packing, file inventory, installation, type checking, client build, SSR build/render, hydration, server-node preservation, Button behavior, Field model and ARIA, CSS assets, tree-shaking, and workspace use.</p>
<h2>Browser proof</h2><p>The production galleries run the installed tarballs at mobile, tablet, and desktop widths. They exercise click behavior, disabled invariants, model updates, label/description/error/required ARIA, CSS, same-origin framing, and network/console health.</p>
<h2>What remains not-run</h2><ul><li>Hot-module replacement as a package gate</li><li>Manual screen-reader sessions</li></ul><p>Those checks remain explicitly <code>not-run</code>; they are not converted into passes.</p>
<h2>Why Select is absent</h2><p>Select has contract and structural evidence, but its framework browser and consumer gates are incomplete or failed. The packages therefore expose Button and Field only. See <a href="/select-pilot/">the Select pilot</a>.</p>
<h2>Separate compiler evidence</h2><p>Planner benchmarks, output-architecture experiments, the immutable 164/164 runtime authority, and package readiness are different claims. A fast planner does not choose an architecture, and a generated source file is not a browser pass.</p>
